    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="323"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Prime Minister</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Churchill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="5" type="source" xml:id="d323fn5">Copy of telegram obtained from the
                        Franklin D. Roosevelt Library at Hyde Park, N.Y.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-13">October 13,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. 796. Your number 628. I have given instructions to the Food Minister that no
                    long-term contract is to be negotiated for the next couple of months or so and
                    that we are to proceed meanwhile on a month to month basis during which time we
                    can discuss the matters further.<note n="6" xml:id="d323fn6">Text of the
                        foregoing sentence amended as requested by Prime Minister Churchill in
                        telegram 797, October 14, 1944, not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>We are worried for fear that French, Belgian and presently the Dutch will come
                    into the market with plenty of gold. Nevertheless we shall make no arrangement
                    at present time but later on I must address you again on the subject.</p>
            </div>
